03:14.160 --> 03:18.200
One thing he feels strongly about is that science fiction has not been treated fairly by book reviewers.

03:19.120 --> 03:27.860
As a category, you know, it is treated very, very unfairly and very cavalierly by the powers that be,

03:27.860 --> 03:35.620
which is mainly the New York Times book review and the New York Review of Books and the so-called New York Literary Establishment,

03:35.640 --> 03:38.720
which really does have a very heavy effect on the way books are published.

03:39.520 --> 03:46.660
These people, for instance, came down on the American Book Awards, succeeded in getting science fiction knocked out of the American Book Awards.

03:47.220 --> 03:54.920
A real small clique of people in New York City who felt that it was really bad to have these awards given to things like science fiction,

03:54.920 --> 04:00.400
that it was bad to take it away from a small jury which they could control and have thousands of people voting for,

04:00.660 --> 04:07.700
a very elitist social fascist bunch of people who I am absolutely no use for, and I'm sure they have no use for me.

04:09.100 --> 04:13.480
As president of the science fiction writers of America, Spinrad has worked for some changes in the field.

04:14.820 --> 04:18.560
One thing that I'm already halfway through getting done is the international audience,

04:19.040 --> 04:22.740
is to have an overseas region with an overseas director on our board of directors.

04:23.340 --> 04:26.520
Science fiction writing and publishing really is an international community.

04:26.940 --> 04:29.460
American writers sell their work all over the world.

04:30.340 --> 04:32.120
English writers sell their work here.

04:32.320 --> 04:36.600
Foreign language writers have different problems and we're all dealing with the same publishers.

04:37.380 --> 04:41.920
It certainly is an international literature and it's the spirit of the future and the spirit of internationalism.

04:42.180 --> 04:45.900
So, of course, I felt it should be an international organization. That's one thing.

04:46.760 --> 04:51.340
The other thing that I want to do and halfway through doing is upgrading the Nebula Awards.

04:51.340 --> 04:55.500
We have moved it out of the World Rec Hotel. We're moving into a much bigger room in the world

04:55.500 --> 04:59.060
offering trying to make it into a more significant event than it has been.

04:59.560 --> 05:03.900
Again, orienting it towards the world at large rather than towards the little in group.

05:05.640 --> 05:09.340
Spinrad has always been concerned with the image science fiction has with the general public.

05:09.660 --> 05:14.860
He thinks general readers should be made more aware of science fiction's unique possibilities and its genuine value.

05:15.220 --> 05:19.840
We asked him if science fiction movies have a positive or negative influence on the public's image of the field.

05:21.000 --> 05:24.020
I don't know. I don't think they...not really.

05:24.540 --> 05:28.060
I mean, the image of science fiction in that respect has been very bad anyway.

05:28.300 --> 05:33.860
I don't think the movies really add to the image, but I don't think they detract from it either.

05:34.080 --> 05:36.880
If there are some better, more sophisticated movies, they might help.

05:38.020 --> 05:42.580
As it is, it's just kind of neutral publicity. People are more aware that it exists.

05:42.740 --> 05:46.660
I think it's positive and will prove to be positive in the long range

05:47.160 --> 05:50.420
because a lot of people are being introduced to the imagery of science fiction

05:50.420 --> 05:52.800
with which they were unfamiliar through these movies.

05:53.600 --> 05:58.380
And if you look at the evolution in the movies, you find that in the earlier science fiction movies,

05:58.680 --> 06:02.580
if you're going into space or whatever, you had to spend like half an hour setting the thing,

06:02.880 --> 06:06.420
this is a spaceship that takes off from the Earth. People float around, you know,

06:06.460 --> 06:10.320
and you have to familiarize the audience with all this unfamiliar imagery.

06:10.520 --> 06:14.800
Now they can just start a movie bang right off, in a galaxy far away. Boom.

06:15.360 --> 06:17.740
Here's a spaceship in the stromo pow, you know.

06:17.760 --> 06:21.580
In other words, the first half hour of the conventional old-time science fiction movie is gone

06:21.580 --> 06:23.780
because people are now familiar with this imagery.

06:24.400 --> 06:29.760
And I think these movies have brought a lot of new people into familiarity with these images.

06:30.200 --> 06:32.440
They made these images part of the popular culture.

06:33.680 --> 06:38.180
These movies have been mainly aimed at kids and adolescents.

06:39.080 --> 06:42.200
And years from now, assuming that these people ever read anything,

06:43.140 --> 06:47.880
they'll be ready to read science fiction of a more serious kind.

06:48.060 --> 06:51.300
Assuming they're ready to read literature of a more serious kind or all,

06:51.680 --> 06:54.800
because they'll be familiar with the material, familiar with the literature.

06:54.940 --> 06:57.960
It won't seem strange and weird to them because they will have grown up with it.

06:58.620 --> 07:01.560
That's why I think magazines, even magazines like Star-Walk say,

07:02.240 --> 07:05.760
in that sense will have a long-term positive impact.

