08:42.560 --> 08:45.500
Norman Spinrad's best-known novel may be Bug Jack Barron,

08:45.720 --> 08:48.520
a book which has stirred controversy in both England and America.

08:48.980 --> 08:53.240
It was published in this country in 1969, and it's a different sort of science fiction novel.

08:53.660 --> 08:55.720
It's a good example of new wave science fiction.

08:56.180 --> 08:59.920
Character and style are important, and it deals with social issues such as racism,

09:00.420 --> 09:03.940
the establishment, drugs, the power of the media, and radical protests.

09:04.420 --> 09:08.080
There is also a good deal of sex and violence in the book, and the language is highly colored.

09:08.080 --> 09:12.300
But Spinrad, thanks to the plot of the book, conforms to traditional science fiction formulas.

09:13.800 --> 09:17.760
Actually, what I was trying to do in a way, the book has a very traditional plot.

09:18.260 --> 09:22.120
As far as I was concerned, it has a positive here, it has negative here.

09:22.440 --> 09:24.160
The hero wins, the villain loses.

09:24.380 --> 09:29.380
All that stuff that is considered the traditional way of plotting a book.

09:30.040 --> 09:32.120
And yet it's written in a different kind of way.

09:32.120 --> 09:37.720
It kind of takes that superficial kind of plot and treats it in a realistic manner.

09:38.820 --> 09:44.780
The protagonist, Jack Barron, is a powerfully influential television star who has a talk show watched by 100 million people.

09:45.400 --> 09:48.660
He uses the show as a battlefield to oppose corrupt elements of society.

09:49.100 --> 09:51.200
Spinrad comments on Barron's use of power.

09:52.180 --> 09:56.000
The book is about power.

09:56.940 --> 09:59.920
Power itself is neutral as far as I'm concerned.

09:59.920 --> 10:01.460
It's what people do with it that counts.

10:02.260 --> 10:07.780
Barron is a guy who likes power and keeps referring to it as a drug.

10:08.780 --> 10:10.900
And knows that he can become addicted to it.

10:11.820 --> 10:14.300
And for that reason, has decided to stay away from it.

10:15.000 --> 10:24.160
Then he gets drawn back into playing with power because he comes to the conclusion that it's better for somebody who feels that way about power to be wielding it,

10:24.460 --> 10:28.640
than people who don't have any self-consciousness about the dangers of wielding power.

10:28.640 --> 10:38.120
So in that sense, it's a comment on the power of the media, but it's also a comment on the morality of power, on the paradox of power,

10:38.220 --> 10:49.820
which is that if you leave power to be wielded by people who do not see the dangers, the personal dangers, the psychological dangers of being involved with it,

10:50.140 --> 10:53.800
then you end up with people like Benedict Howard's Ronald Reagan and Richard Nixon,

10:55.220 --> 11:02.740
who do not have self-consciousness about the personal dangers, the moral dangers of chasing after power.

11:02.860 --> 11:06.920
Whereas somebody like Barron, who is certainly an imperfect person, as old people are,

11:07.540 --> 11:18.040
at least his saving grace, if he has one, is that he is well aware of the personal dangers of being involved in a quest for power.

11:19.200 --> 11:23.700
When Spinrad tried to get the novel published in this country, he was unsuccessful, so he tried and written.

11:24.120 --> 11:27.960
But there was an outcry in Parliament against the book. He relates the story for us.

11:48.040 --> 11:55.960
I saw that book here. In the meantime, I took it to Wilford, to a Wilford conference, and Mike Murcock was there, and he read it, and he liked it, and he serialized it.

11:56.020 --> 11:59.980
New World, so the first publication was actually in England, in the magazine.

12:01.940 --> 12:11.720
Now, halfway through the serialization, I forget exactly which part, part three, part four, W. H. Smith, which was the biggest distributor in England,

12:12.320 --> 12:15.040
refused to distribute the magazine because of the book in it.

12:15.600 --> 12:20.880
Now, at that time, New World had an Arts Council grant. The Arts Council was an organ of the British government.

12:22.060 --> 12:25.680
Now, the Arts Council supported the magazine against Smith publicly.

12:26.760 --> 12:37.000
And so the flap in Parliament arose when certain right-wing members of Parliament were aghast that an organ of the British government, the Arts Council, was defending this kind of stuff.

12:37.660 --> 12:40.300
And that's how it became a parliamentary issue.

